To use AT&T Video Call, all parties must be AT&T customers with Video Call-capable devices, located in AT&T HD Voice coverage, and must have Video Call set up on their account. Each Video Call uses both voice and data. The voice portion of the call counts as voice minutes, and the video portion counts as data under your wireless rate plan. Once you have started a Video Call, it will seamlessly switch to Wi-Fi if your device has access to the Internet through its Wi-Fi connection. To continue a video call on Wi-Fi you must still remain connected to the AT&T wireless network. No voice or data charges apply to Video Call over Wi-Fi. The Video Call icon tells you when you are able to make a video call. Other AT&T subscribers can see if you are capable of receiving video calls. You can disable AT&T Video Call in Call Settings on your device. For more information and restrictions, visit www.att.com/videocall.

Click to launch VVM Test config options

Visual Voicemail:
You can play your voicemails in the order of your choice.
Your most recent voicemails appear at the top of the list.
Premium subscribers have access to voicemail text transcripts. Premium subscribers can also receive voicemails and transcripts of voicemails in their email inbox.

Setup:
If you’re a first time user, you’ll need to set up your voicemail. This is an easy 2-step process that involves choosing a PIN and a voicemail greeting. Your default PIN is the last 4 digits of your phone number, but you’ll need to change it as part of the setup.

Greetings:
You can choose from 3 types of voicemail greetings. These are used to greet your callers when they reach your voicemail.
Custom Greeting: Allows you to record a personal greeting
Name Greeting: Allows you to record your name
Default Greeting: Standard greeting with your phone number

How to change your PIN and greeting?
You can change your PIN and voicemail greeting anytime by going to Settings -> Visual Voicemail.

How to see this tutorial later?
You can revisit this tutorial anytime by going to Settings > Visual Voicemail.

What happens when callers leave a voicemail when you don’t have a data connection?
You’ll always be notified when you receive a new voicemail. You can listen to your voicemails by tapping the “Voicemail” button in your phone app. Your voicemails will download automatically when a data connection is restored.

Are voicemails downloaded automatically?
Voicemails will download automatically when you’re connected to Wi-Fi. When you’re using a mobile network, you can turn on auto download by going to Settings > Visual Voicemail.

"Visual Voice Mail (VVM) is a service that provides access to voice mail messages directly on the device, without the need to call *86. This service requires traditional Voice Mail but does not support all traditional Voice Mail features, which you can access by dialing *86 from your handset. Use of this feature will be billed on a per-megabyte basis, or according to any data package you have. Mobile to mobile minutes do not apply. Standard rates apply to any calls, emails or messages initiated from Visual Voice Mail.
You may disable VVM in settings. This will revert you to basic voice mail. In some cases you may need to call customer care to cancel and if you cancel Visual Voice Mail you may lose all stored voice mails and information.
For the Premium Visual Voice Mail service, some voice messages may not be completely transcribed; incomplete messages will end with [...]. Only the first 45 seconds of each voice message will be transcribed, so for longer messages, you will need to listen to the voice message itself. Any profane or offensive language also will not be transcribed and will appear as [...] in the transcription.
Speech recordings may be collected and stored for a period of 30 days, solely for the purpose of testing and improving transcription technology and performance, subject to the Verizon Wireless Privacy Policy, which can be found at %s
You understand that by selecting ACCEPT, your messages will be stored and anyone in possession of this device will have access to your voice mail. You further understand that your voice mail messages may be stored in electronic format on this device. To limit unauthorized access to your voice mail, you should consider locking your phone when not in use. Not available in all areas or over Wi‚ÄëFi.
If you do not accept all of these terms and conditions, do not use Visual Voice Mail."
